english:
  title: Record of the Hall of Celebration
  author: Ha Ryun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the thirteenth year of my lord's reign, in the second month of spring, the western pavilion behind the palace had tilted dangerously. The office of the Gyeongbokgung reported this to the State Council, and my lord, startled and sighing, said: "This was built by my father when he founded our dynasty. How has it come to this?" He then commanded Minister of Works Park Ja-cheong and others, saying: "The farming season approaches. Let us employ the idle and repair it swiftly."

    So Park and his men surveyed the ground, moved the structure slightly westward, broadened its design upon the same foundation, and rebuilt it anew. Fearing the dampness of the earth, they dug a pond encircling the pavilion. When completed, my lord ascended and observed, saying: "I wished merely to restore what was old. Have we not exceeded the former measure?" Park and the others, prostrating themselves, replied: "We feared, my lord, lest it crumble again. Thus we took these precautions." My lord then gathered the nobility and elders to make merry together, naming the pavilion the Hall of Celebration, and commanded me, Ha Ryun, to compose this record.

    I have long heard the words of Confucius when Duke Ai of Lu asked of governance: "In matters of state, all depends upon securing the right people." Indeed, for a ruler, obtaining virtuous men is the very foundation of governance. Only when we have secured such people can we speak of true celebration.

    My great ancestor, Taejo the Sagacious and Martial, pacified all with his virtue, and the Son of Heaven bestowed upon us the name Joseon. He established the capital on the sunny side of the mountains and built the palace, naming its great hall "Diligent in Government," and making this the name of his dynasty's foundation. My lord, inheriting his virtue, continues this great work with ever greater devotion to the superior power. The Son of Heaven has granted him commissions; his governance shines with benevolence, and the realm rests in peace.

    Even in the repair of a single pavilion, my lord considers the nearness of the farming season and employs only those without livelihood, completing the work without delay. In naming it the Hall of Celebration, he seeks in his leisure moments to receive those ministers of virtue who comprehend the principles of good governance, to hear their counsel and discuss matters of right conduct, thereby establishing the very source of rulership. Herein we see my lord truly understands the foundation of diligent governance.

    I have reflected that the Hall of Celebration represents the auspicious meeting of ruler and minister through virtue. It is as the ninth position in the creative force of the hexagram, wherein great virtue recognizes great virtue in the second position, their aims align and their spirits harmonize, so that virtuous men naturally arise, the state flourishes, and we see the truth of how clouds follow the dragon and winds follow the tiger. Yet if virtue does not govern such meetings, the petty and corrupt gather instead, and the realm falls into darkness. Even when virtuous men do rise, if their talents are not fully employed, if they are mixed among the corrupt, darkness will be the same result.

    Consider the ancients: when Yao and Shun, Yu and Tang, the High Ancestor of Shang, King Wen and King Wu surrounded themselves with Gao Yao, Kui, Yi, Yi Yin, Fu Yue, Lü Shang, Duke of Zhou, and Duke of Shao—this was true celebration. The Han Emperor Gao with Xiao He and Cao Can, Tang Taizong with Fang Xuanling and Wei Zheng, Song Taizu with Zhao Pu—these too might be called celebrations. Yet lacking the purity of virtue, could they compare with the three ancient dynasties?

    The Han Wudi's relationship with Gongsun Hong, the Song Shenzong's with Wang Anshi—meetings they were, yet neither could escape reproach for hollow words or the likeness of great treachery to loyalty. How can these be called celebrations?

    Even Xuanzong with Song Jing and Zhang Jiuling, or Zhenzong with Kou Zhun—these were indeed meetings of some merit. Yet when Li Linfu succeeded them, when Wang Qinruo served alongside, the distinction between pure and corrupt, the separation between fragrant orchid and rotten herb—even these were hard to discern. How much less can true celebration be spoken of?

    Thus we see that the celebration of ruler and minister has been rare throughout all ages. Should fortune grant us such a meeting once in a thousand years, what must be the joy thereof!

    My great ancestor established "Diligent in Government" as the foundation of the realm and ruled accordingly. My lord now establishes the "Hall of Celebration" as the foundation of diligent governance. Ah, how glorious are these beginnings and continuations! That we shall attain the celebrations of the ancient sage-kings, achieve their fruits, and transmit their wisdom eternally to future generations, ensuring blessings without end—of this we may be assured.

    As for the majesty of mountains and waters, the serene depths of gardens and pools, where snow seems born upon one's desk and rivers appear to touch the hall's edge; where pines and cypresses flourish and flowers bloom; where wind and mist, clouds and moon, the changing lights of dawn and dusk manifest themselves before the eye—these I cannot fully describe. Yet in the restoration of this pavilion I perceive an image of statecraft itself. The tilted is made straight, the unstable made secure—thus we preserve what our forebears built. The foundation is strengthened, dampness removed—thus we secure the grand edifice. The beams and pillars are made strong, for what bears great weight cannot be frail. The lesser timbers are completed, for small duties require not those of great stature. The eaves open wide to broaden wisdom. The stairs rise high to establish proper hierarchy. The prospect below inspires reverence. The vista in all directions embraces all under heaven. When swallows come to celebrate, the common people rejoice. When flies cannot alight, the whispers of the treacherous are silenced. The paintings are not lavish, for propriety rests in the mean. Recreation comes in season, for tension and release must be harmonious.

    If, when ascending and descending these stairs, one holds such thoughts in mind and applies them to governance, then the benefit of this hall shall surely be great indeed. Thus do I record these reflections.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Hall of Celebration' (경회루) became one of the most celebrated structures in Korean history, serving as a space for royal gatherings and intellectual discourse.
  - key: ''
    value: Ha Ryun (河崙, 1347-1416) was one of the most prominent Neo-Confucian scholars and officials of early Joseon, serving Taejo and his successors with distinction.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'Diligent in Government' (勤政) reflects the Confucian ideal that governance should be a primary concern of the ruler, not mere ceremony.
  - key: ''
    value: The allusions to historical sage-kings and their ministers (Yao-Shun, Yu, Tang, etc.) establish the philosophical framework that virtue in rulership depends upon the harmony between ruler and wise counselors.
